764/182951/4/135745/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="reviewIntro" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46764" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46764/182951/4/135745/?merchant=Amazon">Uni-ball Signo RT1</a> to the Pentel EnerGel RTX due to the Signo RT1’s understated (albeit all-plastic) design.</p><p>In our tests, the Signo RT1’s performance was nearly identical to that of the EnerGel and the Precise V5 RT (with just a bit of smudging when we forced it). The main difference between these pens is how they look, plus their available colors and tip sizes.</p><p><strong>Style:</strong> rollerball with gel ink<br/><strong>Tip width tested:</strong> 0.5 mm<br/><strong>Widths available:</strong> <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46950/174759/4/135740/?merchant=Amazon" rel="sponsored noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46950/174759/4/135740/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="reviewIntro" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46950" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46950/174759/4/135740/?merchant=Amazon">0.28 mm</a>, <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46955/174764/4/135746/?merchant=Amazon" rel="sponsored noopener" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46955/174764/4/135746/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="reviewIntro" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46955" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46955/174764/4/135746/?merchant=Amazon">0.38 mm</a>, <a class="product-link" 