 pens</a></li><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#the-competition" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="12" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="The competition">The competition</a></li><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#faqs" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="13" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="Frequently asked questions">Frequently asked questions</a></li><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#sources" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="14" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="Sources">Sources</a></li></ul></section></div></div></div><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="why-you-should-trust-us" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="why-you-should-trust-us-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading" data-gtm-trigger="single_chapter" data-chapter-name="Why you should trust us" data-expand-close="close" data-chapter-index="1">Why you should trust us</h2></div></div><div id="why-you-should-trust-us-panel" class="fa265be5" aria-labelledby="why-you-should-trust-us" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><div class=" chapter__content-wrapper"><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Wirecutter senior staff writer Melanie Pinola has researched and written about all types of home-office gear, including <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-notebooks/">notebooks</a>, since 2011. For years, she has written most things in longhand, including article drafts, journal entries, and short stories. And although she’s not as fanatical about stationery as some people, her favorite type of store is an office-supply store.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Our panel of testers included Wirecutter staffers who <em>are </em>fanatical about stationery—they collect pens as a hobby, and they’re more knowledgeable and opinionated about pens than most people. In testing our ergonomic pen options, our panelists included two medical professionals (one who has had rheumatoid arthritis for over 30 years).</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><aside class="d6a9b639" data-scp="inline_recirc" data-testid="recirc-grid"><h4 class="f7b4df64" data-scp="inline_recirc_title hidden">The best mechanical pencil companion to your pen, and best notebook for it</h4><ul class="b3d51331" data-scp="inline_recirc_list"><li class="ba287d6a ed4e7a20" data-related-id="500" data-gtm-element="inline_module" data-inline-module-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-mechanical-pencils/" data-inline-module-index="0" data-scp="inline_recirc_item"><article class="a2173826" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-mechanical-pencils/" data-title="The Best Mechanical Pencils" data-content-type="review" aria-labelledby="group-title-500" aria-describedby="group-text-500"><div class="cde69604" data-scp="removed"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-mechanical-pencils/" tabindex="-1" data-related-id="500" data-inline-module-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-mechanical-pencils/" data-inline-module-index="0" data-gtm-trigger="inline_module"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img loading="lazy" alt="The Best Mechanical Pencils" itemProp="image" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/12/mechanicalpencils-2048px-9812-3x2-1.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=90" data-src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/12/mechanicalpencils-2048px-9812-3x2-1.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=150" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/12/mechanicalpencils-2048px-9812-3x2-1.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=150 768w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/12/mechanicalpencils-2048px-9812-3x2-1.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=150&amp;dpr=1.5 1152w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/12/mechanicalpencils-2048px-9812-3x2-1.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=150&amp;dpr=2 1536w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/12/mechanicalpencils-2048px-9812-3x2-1.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=90 320w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/12/mechanicalpencils-2048px-9812-3x2-1.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=90&amp;dpr=1.5 480w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/12/mechanicalpencils-2048px-9812-3x2-1.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=90&amp;dpr=2 640w" width="150" height="100" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce e7a1aff2 "/></div></a></div><div class="ba3782d5"><h3 class="c89ed24f" data-scp="inline_recirc_headline"><a id="group-title-500" class="f325b457" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-mechanical-pencils/" aria-label="The Best Mechanical Pencils" data-related-id="500" data-inline-module-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-mechanical-pencils/" data-inline-module-index="0" data-gtm-trigger="inline_module">The Best Mechanical Pencils</a></h3><div id="group-text-500" class="fca148e3" data-scp="removed" data-testid="recirc-summary"><p>These mechanical pencils lay down precise lines and are comfortable to hold and nice to look at.</p></div></div></article></li><li class="ba287d6a ed4e7a20" data-related-id="62507" data-gtm-element="inline_module" data-inline-module-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-notebooks/" data-inline-module-index="1" data-scp="inline_recirc_item"><article class="a2173826" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-notebooks/" data-title="The Best Notebooks and Notepads" data-content-type="review" aria-labelledby="group-title-62507" aria-describedby="group-text-62507"><div class="cde69604" data-scp="removed"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-notebooks/" tabindex="-1" data-related-id="62507" data-inline-module-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-notebooks/" data-inline-module-index="1" data-gtm-trigger="inline_module"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img loading="lazy" alt="The Best Notebooks and Notepads" itemProp="image" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2020/11/notebooks-2048px-1981.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=90" data-src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2020/11/notebooks-2048px-1981.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=150" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2020/11/notebooks-2048px-1981.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=150 768w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2020/11/notebooks-2048px-1981.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=150&amp;dpr=1.5 1152w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2020/11/notebooks-2048px-1981.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=150&amp;dpr=2 1536w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2020/11/notebooks-2048px-1981.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=90 320w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2020/11/notebooks-2048px-1981.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=90&amp;dpr=1.5 480w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2020/11/notebooks-2048px-1981.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=3:2&amp;width=90&amp;dpr=2 640w" width="150" height="100" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce e7a1aff2 "/></div></a></div><div class="ba3782d5"><h3 class="c89ed24f" data-scp="inline_recirc_headline"><a id="group-title-62507" class="f325b457" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-notebooks/" aria-label="The Best Notebooks and Notepads" data-related-id="62507" data-inline-module-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-notebooks/" data-inline-module-index="1" data-gtm-trigger="inline_module">The Best Notebooks and Notepads</a></h3><div id="group-text-62507" class="fca148e3" data-scp="removed" data-testid="recirc-summary"><p>These notebook and notepad picks offer a satisfying writing experience with different types of pens and pencils.</p></div></div></article></li></ul></aside></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="who-this-is-for" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="who-this-is-for-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading" data-gtm-trigger="single_chapter" data-chapter-name="Who this is for" data-expand-close="close" data-chapter-index="2">Who this is for</h2></div></div><div id="who-this-is-for-panel" class="fa265be5" aria-labelledby="who-this-is-for" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><div class=" chapter__content-wrapper"><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Like <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-notebooks/">notebooks</a>, <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-pencils/">pencils</a>, and other everyday stationery essentials, pens are a utilitarian tool that most people don’t think much about when they’re buying them. Sometimes you can go long stretches without purchasing any pens, relying instead on freebies from hotels, offices, conferences, and other places to stock your home or desk.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>But if you spend about $2 to $3 to get a good pen, your handwriting could be more attractive—and possibly more readable—thanks to the darker and better-flowing ink.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>And since people have different hand sizes, comfort preferences, and aesthetic sensibilities, it’s worth it to find and invest in a pen with a comfortable grip, a tip size you prefer for your specific handwriting, and a design you like.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <span>majority of</span> pens we recommend all have refillable ink, too, so you can keep the pen body and replace the ink when the original dries up. By using a refillable pen—and actually remembering to refill it—you will reduce the number of pens you buy (or otherwise acquire) and create less waste for the environment.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ff31b4af" data-ad-element="outer_ad_container" data-scp="removed"><div class="e5d43c70"><p class="cca4d3b6">Advertisement</p><a href="#after-dfp-ad-chapter-mid-4" class="css-777zgl">SKIP ADVERTISEMENT</a><div class="ad dfp-ad-chapter-mid-4-wrapper css-rfqw0c" id="dfp-ad-chapter-mid-4"></div><div id="after-dfp-ad-chapter-mid-4"></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="how-we-picked-and-tested" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="how-we-picked-and-tested-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading" data-gtm-trigger="single_chapter" data-chapter-name="How we picked and tested" data-expand-close="close" data-chapter-index="3">How we picked and tested</h2></div></div><div id="how-we-picked-and-tested-panel" class="fa265be5" aria-labelledby="how-we-picked-and-tested" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><div class=" chapter__content-wrapper"><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 bdfcf243"><figure id="attachment_222193" class="wp-caption alignnone"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image b71ff2c5"><img loading="lazy" alt="Six of our favorite pens, shown side-by-side." src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320" data-src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024 1024w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024&amp;dpr=1.5 1536w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024&amp;dpr=2 2048w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980 980w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980&amp;dpr=1.5 1470w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980&amp;dpr=2 1960w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=768 768w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=768&amp;dpr=1.5 1152w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=768&amp;dpr=2 1536w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=480 480w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=480&amp;dpr=1.5 720w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=480&amp;dpr=2 960w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320 320w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320&amp;dpr=1.5 480w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6526.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320&amp;dpr=2 640w" width="2048" height="1365" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce alignnone size-full wp-image-222193"/></div><figcaption class="wp-caption-text"> <!-- --> <span class="wp-caption-text wp-caption-credit">Photo: Michael Hession</span></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>For this guide we focused on inexpensive pens—$5 or less for a basic pen and $15 or less for a specialty pen (including ergonomic and multicolor models). We also targeted pens that can be purchased at big-box retailers, office-supply stores, or major online vendors, such as Amazon.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Following feedback from readers and experts (as well as our own conscience), we also focused on pens that are refillable and therefore more eco-friendly than disposable pens.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>These pens may seem boring, but they’re meaningful upgrades over giveaway pens and are great for everyday carry (EDC). If you want something a bit fancier, we’ve also included, in our <a href="#other-good-pens">Other good pens</a> section, a few recommendations for nicer-looking or more-distinct (yet still under-$20) pens that you might keep at your desk.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>And though we love fountain pens, that’s a whole can of worms we’re saving for another time.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 bdfcf243"><figure id="attachment_222194" class="wp-caption alignnone"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image b71ff2c5"><img loading="lazy" alt="The different tips of our six favorite pens." src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320" data-src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024 1024w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024&amp;dpr=1.5 1536w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024&amp;dpr=2 2048w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980 980w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980&amp;dpr=1.5 1470w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980&amp;dpr=2 1960w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=768 768w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=768&amp;dpr=1.5 1152w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=768&amp;dpr=2 1536w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=480 480w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=480&amp;dpr=1.5 720w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=480&amp;dpr=2 960w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320 320w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320&amp;dpr=1.5 480w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-6528.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320&amp;dpr=2 640w" width="2048" height="1365" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce size-full wp-image-222194"/></div><figcaption class="wp-caption-text"> Our pen picks’ tips range from sharp needlepoints for writing with thin, precise lines to traditional conical shapes best suited to writing at various angles. From left to right: Pilot Precise V5 RT, Pentel EnerGel RTX, Pilot Dr. Grip Center of Gravity, Uni-Ball Jetstream Slim Multi-Color, Uni-ball Jetstream RT, and Uni-ball Signo RT1.<!-- --> <span class="wp-caption-text wp-caption-credit">Photo: Michael Hession</span></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Here’s a quick primer on a few pen terms you’ll see throughout this guide:</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><ul><li><em>Feathering </em>refers to ink bleeding from the edge of letters, versus crisp lettering.</li><li><em>Bleeding </em>refers to ink coming through to the other side of the paper or even to the next sheet.</li><li><em>Skipping </em>refers to ink not consistently connecting lines or letters, particularly when you’re writing in script.</li><li><em>Smudging</em> is when the ink smears and the letters you write blur. It’s particularly noticeable if you write left-handed or try to highlight something you just wrote. (Slow-drying inks that typically smudge can even transfer to other paper.)</li><li><em>Blotting </em>refers to the pooling of ink in one spot when you’re writing, because the paper hasn’t yet absorbed the ink.</li></ul></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>When completing evaluations, each tester used every pen to write at least four pages in a <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46957/174766/4/135748/?merchant=Staples" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Staples" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46957/174766/4/135748/?merchant=Staples" data-vars-store="Staples" data-gtm-context="chapter_how-we-picked-and-tested" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Staples" data-pid="46957" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46957/174766/4/135748/?merchant=Staples">notebook</a> filled with paper that works well with all types of ink. Testers considered:</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><ul><li><b>Ink smoothness: </b>How freely did the ink flow, and how much pressure was needed to write clearly?</li><li><b>Precision and consistency: </b>We looked for pens that create uniform, crisp lines. Was there any smudging, feathering, skipping, or blotting? Did the ink bleed through to another sheet?</li><li><b>Comfort: </b>For example, how easy was it to grip the pen when writing for an hour at a time?</li></ul></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 bdfcf243"><div class="ce43b2db fb2675ba" data-testid="gallery-wrapper"><article class="d63cac99" data-gtm-element="gallery-main" data-testid="gallery"><div class="d1ee6a2a"><aside class="dfb4f088"><div aria-label="Go to Slide 1" tabindex="-1" class="fc4db63f  fd22436a " style="-webkit-transform:translate3d(0%, 0, 0);-moz-transform:translate3d(0%, 0, 0);-ms-transform:translate3d(0%, 0, 0);-o-transform:translate3d(0%, 0, 0);transform:translate3d(0%, 0, 0)" role="button" data-testid="gallery-slide-1"><div data-scp="gallery_main"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image b71ff2c5" style="padding-bottom:50.00%;display:inline"><img loading="lazy" alt="Text written with the ballpoint pens we tested for this review." itemProp="image" data-testid="gallery-image" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2021/09/pens-2048px-ballpointsamples.jpg?auto=webp&amp