ession</span></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob e1e566ad d097cc30" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="d02b79e1 e20b6350" data-scp="callout_label">Also great</h4><div id="callout-chapter-5-6" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="27467"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="27467"><span aria-label="Save Product" class="a478f5d2  " data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="27467"></span></div></div></span><div class="f1cabe17"><div class="f31f6df1"><div class="efc734d0 eae76d54"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27467/143474/4/172241?merchant=Amazon" class="fa8c1483 product-merchant-link-button" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27467/143474/4/172241?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="removed" tabindex="-1" data-pid="27467" data-gtm-context="inline"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="" itemProp="image" data-src="https://phnx-tmp-upload.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/13PF5n7TVLutVGb3U2KIIkzuHu2D7ahs9CDmSdFG.avif" width="570" height="380" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce" loading="lazy"/></div></a></div><div class="ce2bb787"><div><h3 class="b550f131 e26624a1 a1a87f29"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27467/143474/4/172241?merchant=Amazon" class="dfb6b88d" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Sakura Pigma Micron Blister" data-gtm-element="callout_product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="5" data-pid="27467" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27467/143474/4/172241?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product" data-gtm-context="inline">Sakura Pigma Micron Blister</a></h3><h2 class="eafb159a"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27467/143474/4/172241?merchant=Amazon" class="c44f6873" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="The best fineliner" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27467/143474/4/172241?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_title" data-scp="callout_title" data-pid="27467" data-gtm-context="inline">The best fineliner</a></h2></div><p class="ec57f3ca" data-scp="callout_description">This pen’s needlepoint tip produces precise, consistent lines with archival-quality ink.</p><div class="dded66b7"><div data-scp="removed"><h4 class="efa3259d">Buying Options</h4><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27467/143474/4/172241?merchant=Amazon" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="5" data-pid="27467" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27467/143474/4/172241?merchant=Amazon" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$12</span> from <span>Amazon</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>If you want a technical pen for precise drawing and/or writing, we recommend the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27467/143474/4/172240/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="5" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27467/143474/4/172240/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_also-great-sakura-pigma-micron" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="27467" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27467/143474/4/172240/?merchant=Amazon">Sakura Pigma Micron</a>.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p><strong>It produces saturated, predictable lines</strong>. The Micron’s needlepoint tip produced the most stable, consistent strokes—ones that don’t vary in width—of the fineliners and felt-tip pens we tested. Other fineliners we tested, including the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58421/195587/4/172252/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58421/195587/4/172252/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_also-great-sakura-pigma-micron" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="58421" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58421/195587/4/172252/?merchant=Amazon">Staedtler Pigment Liner</a>, were streaky at times. The Micron is available in widths from ultrafine (0.15 mm) to broad (0.7 mm).</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 bdfcf243"><figure id="attachment_344688" class="wp-caption alignnone"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image b71ff2c5"><img loading="lazy" alt="A writing sample from the Sakura Pigma Micron" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320" data-src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024 1024w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024&amp;dpr=1.5 1536w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024&amp;dpr=2 2048w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980 980w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980&amp;dpr=1.5 1470w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980&amp;dpr=2 1960w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=768 768w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=768&amp;dpr=1.5 1152w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=768&amp;dpr=2 1536w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=480 480w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=480&amp;dpr=1.5 720w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=480&amp;dpr=2 960w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320 320w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320&amp;dpr=1.5 480w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-sample.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320&amp;dpr=2 640w" width="2048" height="1112" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce alignnone size-full wp-image-344688"/></div><figcaption class="wp-caption-text"> <!-- --> <span class="wp-caption-text wp-caption-credit">Photo: Melanie Pinola</span></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p><strong>The permanent ink is archival</strong>. The pigment in the Micron resists water, fading, and chemicals, making the pen ideal for writings or drawings that you want to last forever—or checks that you want to secure from check washing. Unlike our other picks, the Micron is labeled as having pH-neutral ink, which means it won’t degrade paper over time.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p><strong>It’s great for use with a ruler or stencils</strong>. Because of the long metal tip, you can use the Micron along the edge of a ruler or template without harming the plastic nib.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 bdfcf243"><figure id="attachment_344687" class="wp-caption alignnone"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image b71ff2c5"><img loading="lazy" alt="The writers&#x27; hand holding the Micron pen" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320" data-src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024 1024w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024&amp;dpr=1.5 1536w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024&amp;dpr=2 2048w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980 980w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980&amp;dpr=1.5 1470w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980&amp;dpr=2 1960w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=768 768w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=768&amp;dpr=1.5 1152w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=768&amp;dpr=2 1536w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=480 480w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=480&amp;dpr=1.5 720w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=480&amp;dpr=2 960w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320 320w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320&amp;dpr=1.5 480w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/10/pens-2048px-micron-in-hand.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320&amp;dpr=2 640w" width="2048" height="1366" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce alignnone size-full wp-image-344687"/></div><figcaption class="wp-caption-text"> <!-- --> <span class="wp-caption-text wp-caption-credit">Photo: Melanie Pinola</span></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p><strong>It offers feedback without being sticky</strong>. The Micron doesn’t glide over paper as smoothly as the Jetstream—there’s some friction or feedback similar to the Pilot Precise V5 RT. That can make for more careful and deliberate writing or sketching. It doesn’t have as much friction as marker-like felt-tip pens such as the Sharpie Felt Tip and Paper Mate Flair pens do.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p><strong>But it’s not refillable</strong>. This high performing pen is the only one we recommend that is disposable. If you’re willing to spend a bit more for a refillable fineliner, consider the Copic Multiliner SP.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p><strong>The pen labeling can be confusing</strong>. These pens are labeled from 003 to 12, but those numbers don’t match up with the pens’ tip sizes. For example, the Micron 02 has a 0.3-mm tip and the 05 has a 0.45-mm tip, according to Sakura. Be aware that the stated tip sizes lay down thicker lines than you might expect; the Micron 08’s 0.5-mm tip is closer to the 1-mm or wider tip of other pens. In clothing terms, these pens can “run large.”</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ff31b4af" data-ad-element="outer_ad_container" data-scp="removed"><div class="e5d43c70"><p class="cca4d3b6">Advertisement</p><a href="#after-dfp-ad-chapter-mid-8" class="css-777zgl">SKIP ADVERTISEMENT</a><div class="ad dfp-ad-chapter-mid-8-wrapper css-rfqw0c" id="dfp-ad-chapter-mid-8"></div><div id="after-dfp-ad-chapter-mid-8"></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="other-good-pens" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="other-good-pens-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading" data-gtm-trigger="single_chapter" data-chapter-name="Other good pens" data-expand-close="close" data-chapter-index="11">Other good pens</h2></div></div><div id="other-good-pens-panel" class="fa265be5" aria-labelledby="other-good-pens" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><div class=" chapter__content-wrapper"><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p><strong>If you sometimes like to write in pencil and want colors other than the standards:</strong> The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46960/174769/4/135753/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46960/174769/4/135753/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_other-good-pens" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46960" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46960/174769/4/135753/?merchant=Amazon">Uni Jetstream 4&amp;1</a> offers that versatility. It adds a green ink and a mechanical pencil (as well as an eraser) to the barrel. However, the 4&amp;1 can cost a bit more than the <a href="#also-great-uni-jetstream-slim-multi-color">Uni Jetstream Slim Multi-Color</a>, and it has a thicker barrel, which some people may not prefer.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p><strong>If you want a relatively inexpensive pen that’s attractive enough to give as a gift:</strong> Consider the <a href="https://www.parkerpen.com/jotter-originals.html" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Parker Jotter</a>. With its slim, tapered design, this iconic, all-metal pen has the most satisfyingly clicky knock of any pen we tested. It’s remarkably affordable compared with other aficionado-approved “high-end” pens, such as the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46963/174772/4/135758/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46963/174772/4/135758/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_other-good-pens" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46963" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46963/174772/4/135758/?merchant=Amazon">Retro 1951 Tornado</a> and the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/56905/192474/4/165766/?merchant=Baronfig" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Baronfig" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/56905/192474/4/165766/?merchant=Baronfig" data-vars-store="Baronfig" data-gtm-context="chapter_other-good-pens" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Baronfig" data-pid="56905" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/56905/192474/4/165766/?merchant=Baronfig">Baron Fig Squire</a>. Because it’s a bit shorter than other pens, the Parker Jotter is great for everyday use, but we wouldn’t want to lose it. We tested the ballpoint and gel ink versions, and we covet both.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p><strong>If you want a pretty pen with a lower center of gravity:</strong> Check out the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46964/174773/4/135759/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46964/174773/4/135759/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_other-good-pens" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46964" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46964/174773/4/135759/?merchant=Amazon">Pilot Acroball 1000</a>. It has a slim and tapered design, similar to that of the Parker Jotter, but only its lower grip section is metal. This moves the pen’s weight toward the bottom and makes it more comfortable to hold and write with than most slim pens. However, this pen doesn’t have as many color- or tip-refill options as the Parker Jotter or our other pen picks.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p><strong>If committing to writing in pen makes you nervous:</strong> Consider <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36970/159477/4/110225/?merchant=Target" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Target" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36970/159477/4/110225/?merchant=Target" data-vars-store="Target" data-gtm-context="chapter_other-good-pens" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Target" data-pid="36970" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36970/159477/4/110225/?merchant=Target">Pilot’s FriXion Clicker Erasable Retractable Gel Pen</a>. It’s the best erasable pen we’ve tested, with quick-drying ink and an easy-to-hold body. It erased more cleanly than the other erasable pens we tested, too. However, it does leave a trace of writing behind, and its overall performance is just okay, with some skipping.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p><strong>If you want a refillable fineliner for drawing and writing</strong>: <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58414/195577/4/172239/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58414/195577/4/172239/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_other-good-pens" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="58414" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58414/195577/4/172239/?merchant=Amazon">The Copic Multiliner SP</a> fits the bill. Not only is the ink refillable, but you can replace the tips as well, whether you need to because the tip has worn down or you need a different size. The Copic wrote smoothly in our tests and it has an attractive metal body, but in one instance the tip bent (be careful with how much pressur you use). It also needs a bit more drying time than the Sakura Pigma Micron.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p><strong>If you like the feel of a marker on paper but want a fine nib size:</strong> Take a look at the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58415/195578/4/172253/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58415/195578/4/172253/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_other-good-pens" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="58415" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58415/195578/4/172253/?merchant=Amazon">Sharpie Felt Tip Pen</a>. It was the only pen in our felt-tip and fineliners tests that didn’t smudge at all. It’s available in a rainbow of colors and writes with that slightly scratchy marker-like feel. We found the black and colored pens to be less vibrant than we were expecting.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>There are other pens we tested and loved that exceeded our (admittedly arbitrary) $20 limit, including the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46965/174774/4/135760/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46965/174774/4/135760/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_other-good-pens" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46965" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46965/174774/4/135760/?merchant=Amazon">Tombow Rollerball</a>, the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46966/192487/4/135761/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46966/192487/4/135761/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_other-good-pens" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46966" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46966/192487/4/135761/?merchant=Amazon">OHTO Horizon Needle Point Knock Ballpoint</a>, the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46967/192488/4/135762/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46967/192488/4/135762/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_other-good-pens" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46967" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46967/192488/4/135762/?merchant=Amazon">OHTO Horizon Gel</a>, and the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27463/143435/4/176462/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27463/143435/4/176462/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_other-good-pens" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="27463" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27463/143435/4/176462/?merchant=Amazon">Caran d’Ache 849</a>. But despite their higher prices, in our tests they didn’t deliver notably better writing performance than our picks. In other words, you’re mainly paying for look and feel—which is not a small thing if you love writing with pens.</p></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="the-competition" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="the-competition-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading" data-gtm-trigger="single_chapter" data-chapter-name="The competition" data-expand-close="close" data-chapter-index="12">The competition</h2></div></div><div id="the-competition-panel" class="fa265be5" aria-labelledby="the-competition" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><div class=" chapter__content-wrapper"><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p><em>This is not a comprehensive list of all pens we’ve tested. We have removed pens that are no longer available or that do not meet our testing criteria.</em></p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46766/198200/4/135754/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46766/198200/4/135754/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46766" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46766/198200/4/135754/?merchant=Amazon">Pilot Dr. Grip Limited</a>, for example, has an ergonomic design similar to that of the <a href="#also-great-pilot-dr-grip-center-of-gravity">Dr. Grip Center of Gravity</a> ballpoint, but the Limited version’s gel ink smudged.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27486/175121/4/135778/?merchant=Staples" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Staples" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27486/175121/4/135778/?merchant=Staples" data-vars-store="Staples" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Staples" data-pid="27486" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27486/175121/4/135778/?merchant=Staples">Uni-ball Signo 307</a>, a former pick, produced inconsistent lines (some thick and some thin) and smudged. And, unlike the <a href="#also-great-pilot-precise-v5-rt">Pilot Precise V5</a>, it isn’t refillable.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/45521/172548/4/135765/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/45521/172548/4/135765/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="45521" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/45521/172548/4/135765/?merchant=Amazon">Paper Mate InkJoy</a> wrote with dark gel ink, but it smudged, and it isn’t refillable, unlike the <a href="#also-great-pentel-energel-rtx">Pentel EnerGel</a> and the <a href="#also-great-uni-ball-signo-rt1">Uni-ball Signo RT1</a>.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46969/174778/4/135766/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46969/174778/4/135766/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46969" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46969/174778/4/135766/?merchant=Amazon">Lamy Safari</a> rollerball was well liked by only one of our seven testers; most preferred our other picks, with their thinner barrels, which are interchangeable with other brands’ refills.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46768/174461/4/135749/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46768/174461/4/135749/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46768" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46768/174461/4/135749/?merchant=Amazon">Zebra Pen F-301</a> produced fainter lines than other ballpoints, and its ribbed plastic grip was uncomfortable to hold.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Similarly, the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46765/174458/4/135767/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46765/174458/4/135767/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46765" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46765/174458/4/135767/?merchant=Amazon">Pilot The Better Ballpoint</a>’s ink was a bit light, the plastic grip uncomfortable to hold, and the pen body too rattly.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/490/1372/4/135768/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/490/1372/4/135768/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="490" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/490/1372/4/135768/?merchant=Amazon">Uni-ball Alpha-Gel</a> and the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46970/174779/4/135769/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46970/174779/4/135769/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46970" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46970/174779/4/135769/?merchant=Amazon">Pilot Juice Up 04 Knock</a> both skipped and required more pressure when writing than the <a href="#our-pick-uni-ball-jetstream-rt">Jetstream RT</a>.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46971/174780/4/135770/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46971/174780/4/135770/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46971" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46971/174780/4/135770/?merchant=Amazon">Morning Glory Pro Mach</a> rollerball produced thicker, more-inconsistent lines than its 0.38-mm pen tip should have, and its pen cap required some force to remove.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46972/174781/4/135771/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46972/174781/4/135771/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46972" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46972/174781/4/135771/?merchant=Amazon">Stabilo Worker Colorful Rollerball</a>’s heavy, thick ink blotted and smudged in our tests, and the barrels (which are perhaps too brightly colored) aren’t refillable.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46959/174768/4/135752/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46959/174768/4/135752/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="46959" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/46959/174768/4/135752/?merchant=Amazon">Pilot Hi-Tec-C Coleto</a> multicolor pen has slots for five ink colors and over a dozen color-refill options—more than our multicolor pen pick, the <a href="#also-great-uni-jetstream-slim-multi-color">Uni Jetstream Slim Multi-Color</a>. But it also has a shorter grip section than the Jetstream RT, so it’s less comfortable to hold if you don’t normally hold a pen near the tip. One of its ink slots was impossible to use, and the pen we tested kept getting stuck. This is an issue <a href="https://amazon.com/product-reviews/B0773KHNR9/?ie=UTF8&amp;filterByStar=critical&amp;reviewerType=all_reviews&amp;pageNumber=1#reviews-filter-bar&amp;tag=thewire06-20&amp;linkCode=xm2&amp;ascsubtag=YT462" rel="noopener" target="_blank">several owners have reported on Amazon</a>.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/5542/15778/4/78097/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/5542/15778/4/78097/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="5542" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/5542/15778/4/78097/?merchant=Amazon">Pilot G2</a>, though highly popular, didn’t compare well against other pens. It skipped, feathered, and blobbed more than our picks, and it also took a notably long time to dry.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27508/143622/4/78098/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27508/143622/4/78098/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="27508" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27508/143622/4/78098/?merchant=Amazon">Sharpie Pen</a> is technically a marker with a very fine tip, so it feels different from nearly any other pen, and that made it divisive for our testers.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Schneider pens, including the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27510/143640/4/78101/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27510/143640/4/78101/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="27510" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27510/143640/4/78101/?merchant=Amazon">Slider Rave XB</a> and <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27511/143649/4/78102/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27511/143649/4/78102/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="27511" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27511/143649/4/78102/?merchant=Amazon">Slider Basic</a>, are smoother and faster-drying than a typical cheap office pen. But these German-made pens aren’t as widely available as our picks, and we found the Basic’s thin grip less comfortable to hold than those of other pens we tested.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The Bic Atlantis (available in <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27512/192489/4/165767/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27512/192489/4/165767/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="27512" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27512/192489/4/165767/?merchant=Amazon">0.7-mm</a> and <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27512/192489/4/165768/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27512/192489/4/165768/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="27512" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27512/192489/4/165768/?merchant=Amazon">1.0-mm</a> tips) was recommended to us by commenters as well as by a couple of pen enthusiasts at a coworking space, who called them a good-enough upgrade from traditional Bic sticks and crystal pens. But the Atlantis blobbed and feathered more than any of our picks. It’s better than the cheapest pens at the store, but you can find the far better Precise V5 RT on the same shelf.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Office Depot’s TUL brand is available in a <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27545/143822/4/165769/?merchant=Office%20Depot" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Office Depot" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27545/143822/4/165769/?merchant=Office%20Depot" data-vars-store="Office Depot" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Office Depot" data-pid="27545" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27545/143822/4/165769/?merchant=Office%20Depot">gel pen</a> and a <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27546/143826/4/165770/?merchant=Office%20Depot" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Office Depot" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27546/143826/4/165770/?merchant=Office%20Depot" data-vars-store="Office Depot" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Office Depot" data-pid="27546" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27546/143826/4/165770/?merchant=Office%20Depot">ballpoint</a>. Their exclusivity makes them less interesting as a generally recommended pen (and you can buy all of our other picks at Office Depot). Reviewers <a href="https://nopenintended.wordpress.com/2015/09/08/tul-pens-serious-ink/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">ding the gel pen</a> for its long drying time, and they <a href="https://www.wellappointeddesk.com/2015/06/review-new-tul-serious-ink-pens-from-office-depotmax/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">recommend the line more for stocking an office</a> than for getting a nice pen for yourself.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>We considered the very wide array of Uni-ball pens for this updated guide, and we tried the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27514/143675/4/78105/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27514/143675/4/78105/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="27514" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/27514/143675/4/78105/?merchant=Amazon">Vision Elite with BLX inks</a>. For everyday writing, this pen is very, very wet, and it will likely leave the side of your pinkie or palm shellacked with dark ink. For anyone who wants a bold, colorful pen to do sketches or illustrations, this pen’s color selection and dark, thick ink may appeal.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Of the erasable pens we tested, here’s what we found: The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36973/159480/4/110228/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36973/159480/4/110228/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="36973" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36973/159480/4/110228/?merchant=Amazon">ParKoo Retractable Erasable Gel Pens</a> were a little streakier than the <a href="#other-good-pens">Pilot FriXion</a> pens. The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36974/159481/4/110229/?merchant=Target" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Target" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36974/159481/4/110229/?merchant=Target" data-vars-store="Target" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Target" data-pid="36974" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36974/159481/4/110229/?merchant=Target">Pilot Erasable FriXion ColorSticks</a> didn’t have a grip that would allow someone to comfortably write for a long time. The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36976/192491/4/165771/?merchant=JetPens" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="JetPens" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36976/192491/4/165771/?merchant=JetPens" data-vars-store="JetPens" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="JetPens" data-pid="36976" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36976/192491/4/165771/?merchant=JetPens">R:E Erasable Gel Pen</a>’s off-black ink was too light for our taste. And <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36977/159484/4/110232/?merchant=Walmart" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Walmart" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36977/159484/4/110232/?merchant=Walmart" data-vars-store="Walmart" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Walmart" data-pid="36977" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/36977/159484/4/110232/?merchant=Walmart">Paper Mate’s EraserMate Erasable Pens</a> were drier than the others we tried and didn’t erase as well.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58416/195581/4/172248/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58416/195581/4/172248/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="58416" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58416/195581/4/172248/?merchant=Amazon">Zebra Clickart</a> felt-tip pens produced saturated but very thick lines, and they were hard to write precisely with. One of the pens dried out quickly despite marketing claims that the ink is long lasting. (Also, they don’t have a microSD slot with 512 GB of storage, contrary to Amazon’s listing.)</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10245/156373/4/184172/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10245/156373/4/184172/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="10245" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10245/156373/4/184172/?merchant=Amazon">Paper Mate Flair</a> felt-tip pens felt too sticky against the page—almost like trying to write on the adhesive side of tape. The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58417/195582/4/172247/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58417/195582/4/172247/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="58417" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58417/195582/4/172247/?merchant=Amazon">Amazon Basics Felt Tip Marker Pens</a> and the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58418/195583/4/172246/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58418/195583/4/172246/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="58418" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58418/195583/4/172246/?merchant=Amazon">Mr. Pen Felt Tip Pens</a> likewise were not as smooth as the Micron.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58419/195584/4/172245/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58419/195584/4/172245/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_the-competition" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="58419" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/58419/195584/4/172245/?merchant=Amazon">Stabilo Fineliner</a>’s thin, hexagonal body was uncomfortable to hold for several of our testers, and its signature orange color was divisive.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ff31b4af" data-ad-element="outer_ad_container" data-scp="removed"><div class="e5d43c70"><p class="cca4d3b6">Advertisement</p><a href="#after-dfp-ad-chapter-mid-9" class="css-777zgl">SKIP ADVERTISEMENT</a><div class="ad dfp-ad-chapter-mid-9-wrapper css-rfqw0c" id="dfp-ad-chapter-mid-9"></div><div id="after-dfp-ad-chapter-mid-9"></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="faqs" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="faqs-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading" data-gtm-trigger="single_chapter" data-chapter-name="Frequently asked questions" data-expand-close="close" data-chapter-index="13">Frequently asked questions</h2></div></div><div id="faqs-panel" class="fa265be5" aria-labelledby="faqs" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="d75af381 f0e70157"><div class="f024091c"><div class="e970e32a"><h3 class="b819dcc5">What&#x27;s the difference between a rollerball and a ballpoint pen?</h3><div class="f4b14e5a"><p>Rollerball pens use a water-based ink that flows smoothly and usually creates a lighter, finer line on the paper. Ballpoint pens use an oil-based ink that’s thicker and usually creates a thicker line. Ballpoint pens also tend to require more pressure when writing than rollerball pens.</p></div></div><div class="e970e32a"><h3 class="b819dcc5">What&#x27;s the best pen for lefties?</h3><div class="f4b14e5a"><p>Ballpoint pens, like the <a href="#our-pick-uni-ball-jetstream-rt">Uni-ball Jetstream RT</a>, have ink that dries quickly, so they’re ideal for anyone concerned with smudging. Left-handed people should try to avoid rollerball or gel pens since their ink tends to take longer to dry and smudges more during writing.</p></div></div><div class="e970e32a"><h3 class="b819dcc5">How do you refill an ink pen?</h3><div class="f4b14e5a"><p>Every pen has its own unique refill cartridge and process, so start by looking up what kind of refill your pen needs. This guide can help you <a href="https://www.jetpens.com/blog/The-Ultimate-Guide-to-Pen-Refills/pt/231" rel="noopener" target="_blank">figure out what to look for</a>.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="sources" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="sources-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading" data-gtm-trigger="single_chapter" data-chapter-name="Sources" data-expand-close="close" data-chapter-index="14">Sources</h2></div></div><div id="sources-panel" class="fa265be5 cca5b811" aria-labelledby="sources" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><ol class="e2f33127"><li class="c4d81cbc" data-scp="sources_item"><p data-scp="sources_content">Ana Reinert, <!-- -->email interview<!-- -->, July 15, 2021</p></li><li class="c4d81cbc" data-scp="sources_item"><p data-scp="sources_content">Brad Dowdy, <!-- -->email interview<!-- -->, July 12, 2021</p></li></ol></div></div></div></div></section></div><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502 d4b00d15"><div data-scp="removed"><a id="author-bios"></a><h2 class="bcd0fe8e" data-testid="author-bio-title">Meet your <!-- -->guide</h2><div class="b56e1312"><div class="db49d064 e1e26e10 c5d85fe0"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image b13cc510"><img loading="lazy" alt="" itemProp="image" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/pinola-melanie.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=1:1&amp;width=100" data-src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/